3	tables	public.deviations	public.deviations	Table · 643 rows	# public.deviations\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\nThe `deviations` table has 12 columns and 643 rows. It has foreign keys to `public.production_runs.run_id` (via `run_id`), `public.equipment.equipment_id` (via `equipment_id`).\n\n\n<!-- provenance: claude, 2026-05-19, model=deepseek/deepseek-chat-v3.1 -->\n## What this table represents\nThe table records deviations from expected operating conditions during production runs, such as pressure, temperature, or vibration anomalies, linked to specific equipment. Each row captures when a deviation was detected, its severity, and whether it was resolved.\n\n## Common joins\n- `JOIN public.equipment e ON d.equipment_id = e.equipment_id`\n- `JOIN public.production_runs pr ON d.run_id = pr.run_id`\n\n## Column meanings\n- `deviation_id` — unique identifier for each deviation record.\n- `run_id` — links to the production run during which the deviation occurred.\n- `equipment_id` — identifies the equipment where the deviation was detected.\n- `observed_at` — timestamp when the deviation was first observed.\n- `category` — type of deviation, e.g., pressure, temperature, alignment.\n- `severity` — how severe the deviation is: critical, high, medium, low.\n- `expected_value` — expected operational value; nullable for non-numeric deviations.\n- `actual_value` — measured value during the deviation.\n- `unit` — unit of measure for expected/actual values; nullable if not applicable.\n- `notes` — free-text details, either auto-generated or from operator investigation.\n- `resolved_at` — when the deviation was resolved; null if still open.\n- `root_cause_code` — always null in this sample; likely intended for categorization of causes.\n\n## Likely filter patterns\n- `WHERE d.observed_at >= NOW() - INTERVAL '30 days'`\n- `WHERE d.actual_value IS NOT NULL AND d.expected_value IS NOT NULL`\n- `WHERE d.actual_value <> d.expected_value`\n- `WHERE e.line_id = 'LINE-B'`\n\n<!-- pro