4	tables	public.equipment	public.equipment	Table · 10 rows	# public.equipment\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\nThe `equipment` table has 7 columns and 10 rows.\n\n\n<!-- provenance: claude, 2026-05-19, model=deepseek/deepseek-chat-v3.1 -->\n## What this table represents\nThis table contains master data for industrial processing equipment, tracking each machine's location, manufacturer, installation date, and maintenance schedule within a production facility.\n\n## Common joins\n* `JOIN public.deviations d ON d.equipment_id = e.equipment_id` (from Query 4, 5, 7)\n* `LEFT JOIN public.deviations d ON e.equipment_id = d.equipment_id` (from Query 6, 8)\n\n## Column meanings\n* `equipment_id` — Primary key identifier for a piece of equipment.\n* `line_id` — The production line where the equipment is installed (e.g., 'LINE-A').\n* `name` — The unique, descriptive name of the equipment (e.g., 'Capper-A2').\n* `manufacturer` — The company that manufactured the equipment.\n* `installed_at` — The date the equipment was installed in the facility.\n* `last_maintenance_at` — The timestamp of the most recent maintenance performed.\n* `next_maintenance_due` — The timestamp when the next scheduled maintenance is due.\n\n## Likely filter patterns\n* `WHERE line_id = 'LINE-A'` (from Query 2 and 3)\n* `WHERE next_maintenance_due <= CURRENT_DATE + INTERVAL '30 days'` (inferred from maintenance status logic in Query 1)\n* `WHERE name ILIKE '%naruto%' OR manufacturer ILIKE '%naruto%'` (inferred from text search pattern in Query 10)\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n## Columns\n\n| Column | Type | Null rate | Distinct | PK | FK |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| `equipment_id` | integer | 0.0% | 10 | ✓ |  |\n| `line_id` | text | 0.0% | 4 |  |  |\n| `name` | text | 0.0% | 10 |  |  |\n| `manufacturer` | text | 0.0% | 6 |  |  |\n| `installed_at` | date | 0.0% | 6 |  |  |\n| `last_maintenance_at` | timestamp with time zone | 0.0% | 10 |  |  |\n| `next_maintenance_due` | timestamp with time zone | 0.0% | 10 |  |  |\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `equipment_id` (integer)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 10\n- Min: `1`\n- Max: `10`\n- Top values:\n  - `2` (1)\n  - `10` (1)\n  - `6` (1)\n  - `8` (1)\n  - `9` (1)\n- Histogram (10 bins): 1:1, 10:1, 2:1, 3:1, 4:1, 5:1, 6:1, 7:1, 8:1, 9:1\n- Sample values: `1`, `10`, `2`, `3`, `4`\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `line_id` (text)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 4\n- Min: `LINE-A`\n- Max: `LINE-D`\n- Top values:\n  - `LINE-A` (3)\n  - `LINE-D` (3)\n  - `LINE-C` (2)\n  - `LINE-B` (2)\n- Sample values: `LINE-A`, `LINE-B`, `LINE-C`, `LINE-D`\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `name` (text)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 10\n- Min: `Capper-A2`\n- Max: `Palletizer-D3`\n- Top values:\n  - `Extruder-C1` (1)\n  - `Cooler-C2` (1)\n  - `Labeler-A3` (1)\n  - `Mixer-D1` (1)\n  - `Capper-B2` (1)\n- Sample values: `Capper-A2`, `Capper-B2`, `Cooler-C2`, `Extruder-C1`, `Filler-A1`\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `manufacturer` (text)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 6\n- Min: `Buhler`\n- Max: `Tetra Pak`\n- Top values:\n  - `GEA` (2)\n  - `Tetra Pak` (2)\n  - `Krones AG` (2)\n  - `Sidel` (2)\n  - `Coperion` (1)\n- Sample values: `Buhler`, `Coperion`, `GEA`, `Krones AG`, `Sidel`\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `installed_at` (date)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 6\n- Min: `2017-11-22`\n- Max: `2022-04-18`\n- Top values:\n  - `2017-11-22` (2)\n  - `2021-07-15` (2)\n  - `2018-09-30` (2)\n  - `2019-05-12` (2)\n  - `2022-04-18` (1)\n- Sample values: `2017-11-22`, `2018-09-30`, `2019-05-12`, `2020-02-04`, `2021-07-15`\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `last_maintenance_at` (timestamp with time zone)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 10\n- Min: `2026-02-19 06:00:00+00`\n- Max: `2026-04-28 06:00:00+00`\n- Top values:\n  - `2026-03-30 06:00:00+00` (1)\n  - `2026-04-28 06:00:00+00` (1)\n  - `2026-04-12 06:00:00+00` (1)\n  - `2026-04-10 06:00:00+00` (1)\n  - `2026-04-22 06:00:00+00` (1)\n- Sample values: `2026-02-19 06:00:00+00`, `2026-03-25 06:00:00+00`, `2026-03-30 06:00:00+00`, `2026-04-05 06:00:00+00`, `2026-04-10 06:00:00+00`\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `next_maintenance_due` (timestamp with time zone)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 10\n- Min: `2026-05-19 06:00:00+00`\n- Max: `2026-07-28 06:00:00+00`\n- Top values:\n  - `2026-06-22 06:00:00+00` (1)\n  - `2026-06-12 06:00:00+00` (1)\n  - `2026-07-28 06:00:00+00` (1)\n  - `2026-06-10 06:00:00+00` (1)\n  - `2026-05-30 06:00:00+00` (1)\n- Sample values: `2026-05-19 06:00:00+00`, `2026-05-25 06:00:00+00`, `2026-05-30 06:00:00+00`, `2026-06-05 06:00:00+00`, `2026-06-10 06:00:00+00`\n\n\n\n## Used in views\n\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_equipment_deviation_severity_90d]] — Equipment deviation counts by severity level for the last 90 days (auto-seeded by Loom. Reason: Equipment maintenance teams need to identify which equipment is generating the most severe deviations to prioritize maintenance and repairs)\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_operators_d6cbb6]] — Auto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "who is naruto?"\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_equipment_deviation_summary_30d]] — Shows deviation volume and severity per piece of equipment over the last 30 days, linked to equipment location (line) for failure hotspot analysis. (auto-seeded by Loom. Reason: Identifies problematic equipment by line and severity, crucial for maintenance prioritization and root cause analysis.)\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_equipment_failure_rates_by_line_90d]] — Equipment failure rates and severity distribution by production line for the last 90 days (auto-seeded by Loom. Reason: Identifies problematic equipment and lines for maintenance prioritization and operational improvements)\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_equipment_deviation_analysis_30d]]\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_equipment_e45131]] — Auto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "Nono just equiments"\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_deviations_54ac49]] — Auto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "Nono just equiments"\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_equipment_9e6d45]] — Auto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "Nono just equiments"\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_deviations_e268da]] — Auto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "What should i do to fix this?"\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_deviations_b95d25]] — Auto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "What should i do to fix this?"\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_equipment_by_line]] — Lists all equipment organized by production line with installation and maintenance details\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_production_runs_f9eee5]] — Auto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "What machines are running today on line A"\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_line_a_equipment_status]] — Shows all equipment installed on LINE-A with maintenance status and recent production activity\n	{"name": "equipment", "schema": "public", "is_view": false, "table_id": 2}	de4f1bdeee111b10a338734bef6d5d7b	ready	2026-05-20 08:54:07.948556+00	2026-05-20 08:54:07.948556+00	2026-05-16 19:16:28.350144+00	2026-05-20 08:54:07.948556+00	17	source	tables	\N	\N
2	tables	loom_views.v_deviations_0de189	loom_views.v_deviations_0de189  (view)	Saved view · 4 rows	# loom_views.v_deviations_0de189\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\nThis is a **view** created by Loom. 4 rows as of 2026-05-16.\n\n<!-- provenance: claude, 2026-05-16 -->\n## What this view represents\nAuto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "What is our deviation rate by line over the last 30 days?"\n\n## Definition\n\n```sql\nSELECT \n  pr.line_id,\n  COUNT(*) AS total_deviations,\n  COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE d.actual_value <> d.expected_value) AS deviations_with_mismatch,\n  COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE d.actual_value <> d.expected_value)::float / NULLIF(COUNT(*), 0) AS deviation_rate\nFROM public.deviations d\nJOIN public.production_runs pr ON d.run_id = pr.run_id\nWHERE d.observed_at >= NOW() - INTERVAL '30 days'\nGROUP BY pr.line_id\nORDER BY deviation_rate DESC\n```\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n## Columns\n\n| Column | Type |\n| --- | --- |\n| `line_id` | text |\n| `total_deviations` | bigint |\n| `deviations_with_mismatch` | bigint |\n| `deviation_rate` | double precision |\n\n	{"name": "v_deviations_0de189", "schema": "loom_views", "is_view": true, "table_id": 455}	d3109381e3963f8deb07115643bcd0ef	ready	2026-05-16 19:16:28.345524+00	2026-05-20 08:54:07.871485+00	2026-05-16 19:16:28.345524+00	2026-05-16 19:16:28.345524+00	\N	source	views	\N	\N
33	tables	loom_views.v_run_with_deviation_metrics_30d	loom_views.v_run_with_deviation_metrics_30d  (view)	Saved view · 310 rows	# loom_views.v_run_with_deviation_metrics_30d\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\nThis is a **view** created by Loom. 310 rows as of 2026-05-17.\n\n<!-- provenance: claude, 2026-05-17 -->\n## What this view represents\nJoins production runs with deviation counts and quality failure rates for comprehensive run-level analysis. (auto-seeded by Loom. Reason: Provides a holistic view of each production run's quality and deviation profile, central for batch traceability and RCA.)\n\n## Definition\n\n```sql\nSELECT pr.run_id, pr.line_id, pr.batch_id, pr.product_sku, pr.started_at, pr.ended_at, pr.units_target, pr.units_produced, COUNT(DISTINCT d.deviation_id) AS deviation_count, SUM(CASE WHEN d.resolved_at IS NULL AND d.deviation_id IS NOT NULL THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS open_deviation_count, COUNT(q.check_id) AS quality_check_count, SUM(CASE WHEN q.in_spec = FALSE THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) AS quality_failure_count FROM public.production_runs pr LEFT JOIN public.deviations d ON pr.run_id = d.run_id LEFT JOIN public.quality_checks q ON pr.run_id = q.run_id WHERE pr.started_at >= NOW() - INTERVAL '30 days' GROUP BY pr.run_id, pr.line_id, pr.batch_id, pr.product_sku, pr.started_at, pr.ended_at, pr.units_target, pr.units_produced ORDER BY pr.started_at DESC\n```\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n## Columns\n\n| Column | Type |\n| --- | --- |\n| `run_id` | bigint |\n| `line_id` | text |\n| `batch_id` | text |\n| `product_sku` | text |\n| `started_at` | timestamp with time zone |\n| `ended_at` | timestamp with time zone |\n| `units_target` | integer |\n| `units_produced` | integer |\n| `deviation_count` | bigint |\n| `open_deviation_count` | bigint |\n| `quality_check_count` | bigint |\n| `quality_failure_count` | bigint |\n\n	{"name": "v_run_with_deviation_metrics_30d", "schema": "loom_views", "is_view": true, "table_id": 1125}	e588c9b36269e2c8991a2d5f97a55922	ready	2026-05-17 02:01:15.995682+00	2026-05-20 08:54:07.941319+00	2026-05-17 02:01:15.995682+00	2026-05-17 02:01:15.995682+00	\N	source	tables	\N	\N
55	code	jsonschema-spec-adr	jsonschema-spec / adr	This module contains Architectural Decision Records (ADRs) that document key technical and process decisions for the JSON Schema specification, including changes to keyword behavior, release managemen	## What this module does\nThis module contains Architectural Decision Records (ADRs) that document key technical and process decisions for the JSON Schema specification, including changes to keyword behavior, release management, and community governance. These records capture the rationale behind significant shifts in the project's direction and serve as a historical reference for implementers and contributors.\n\n## Public surface\n- `adr/2022-04-08-cref-for-ambiguity-and-fix-later-gh-spec-issue-1172.md`\n- `adr/2022-09-decouple-from-ietf.md`\n- `adr/2022-11-stable-spec.md`\n- `adr/2023-04-sva-prefix.md`\n- `adr/2024-02-object-contains.md`\n- `adr/2024-05-08-extract-unstable-keywords.md`\n\n## Dependencies & data\n- References GitHub issues, discussions, and pull requests from the `json-schema-org` organization\n- No external libraries or database tables\n\n## When to reference\n- When understanding the historical context behind a specific JSON Schema keyword behavior change, such as the reversion of `contains` for objects or the adoption of the `x-` prefix for single-value annotations.\n- When evaluating the project's transition from IETF-based processes to a independent, stability-focused release cycle.\n- When determining which features are considered unstable or experimental in the current specification release.	{"files": ["adr/2022-04-08-cref-for-ambiguity-and-fix-later-gh-spec-issue-1172.md", "adr/2022-09-decouple-from-ietf.md", "adr/2022-11-stable-spec.md", "adr/2023-04-sva-prefix.md", "adr/2024-02-object-contains.md", "adr/2024-05-08-extract-unstable-keywords.md", "adr/2024-11-2-assertion-format.md", "adr/README.md", "adr/template.md"], "module": "adr", "code_source_id": 2}	ae78da68f02eac825136f25d4c6cb698	ready	2026-05-19 19:14:29.057337+00	2026-05-19 19:14:29.057337+00	2026-05-19 19:14:29.057337+00	2026-05-19 19:14:29.057337+00	\N	source	code	\N	\N
39	tables	loom_views.v_deviations_46ea9c	loom_views.v_deviations_46ea9c  (view)	Saved view · 4 rows	# loom_views.v_deviations_46ea9c\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\nThis is a **view** created by Loom. 4 rows as of 2026-05-17.\n\n<!-- provenance: claude, 2026-05-17 -->\n## What this view represents\nAuto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "What's our deviation rate by production line over the last 30 days?"\n\n## Definition\n\n```sql\nSELECT \n  pr.line_id,\n  COUNT(d.deviation_id) as total_deviations,\n  COUNT(d.deviation_id) FILTER (WHERE d.actual_value <> d.expected_value) as deviations_with_mismatch,\n  COUNT(d.deviation_id) FILTER (WHERE d.actual_value <> d.expected_value)::float / NULLIF(COUNT(d.deviation_id), 0) as deviation_rate\nFROM public.deviations d\nJOIN public.production_runs pr ON d.run_id = pr.run_id\nWHERE d.observed_at >= CURRENT_DATE - INTERVAL '30 days'\nGROUP BY pr.line_id\nORDER BY deviation_rate DESC\n```\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n## Columns\n\n| Column | Type |\n| --- | --- |\n| `line_id` | text |\n| `total_deviations` | bigint |\n| `deviations_with_mismatch` | bigint |\n| `deviation_rate` | double precision |\n\n	{"name": "v_deviations_46ea9c", "schema": "loom_views", "is_view": true, "table_id": 1521}	15da39c66ae983141f11d8bd2fda2d31	ready	2026-05-17 20:15:40.877049+00	2026-05-20 08:54:07.880125+00	2026-05-17 20:15:40.877049+00	2026-05-17 20:15:40.877049+00	\N	source	tables	\N	\N
10	tables	loom_views.v_deviations_61c4f3	loom_views.v_deviations_61c4f3  (view)	Saved view · 24 rows	# loom_views.v_deviations_61c4f3\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\nThis is a **view** created by Loom. 24 rows as of 2026-05-16.\n\n<!-- provenance: claude, 2026-05-16 -->\n## What this view represents\nAuto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "Which pharma company is leading in antibiotics"\n\n## Definition\n\n```sql\nSELECT \n    d.category,\n    d.severity,\n    COUNT(*) as deviation_count,\n    AVG(CASE WHEN d.resolved_at IS NULL THEN 1 ELSE 0 END) as unresolved_rate\nFROM public.deviations d\nGROUP BY d.category, d.severity\nORDER BY deviation_count DESC\n```\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n## Columns\n\n| Column | Type |\n| --- | --- |\n| `category` | text |\n| `severity` | text |\n| `deviation_count` | bigint |\n| `unresolved_rate` | numeric |\n\n	{"name": "v_deviations_61c4f3", "schema": "loom_views", "is_view": true, "table_id": 662}	fa42538021376d498ef4f3e6c4e123ec	ready	2026-05-16 19:31:28.382744+00	2026-05-20 08:54:07.882297+00	2026-05-16 19:31:28.382744+00	2026-05-16 19:31:28.382744+00	\N	source	tables	\N	\N
9	docs	loom-test-doc	loom-test-doc.md	This document outlines the investigation process for elevated deviation rates on Line B, specifically for the Filler-B1 and Capper-B2 equipment, intended for quality engineers and operators.	## What it is\nThis document outlines the investigation process for elevated deviation rates on Line B, specifically for the Filler-B1 and Capper-B2 equipment, intended for quality engineers and operators.\n\n## Key points\n- Invoke the runbook when the **LINE-B deviation rate** exceeds "1.0 deviations per run (24h rolling window)".\n- "deviation rate > 1.5 per run" triggers immediate escalation: "page the on-call engineer immediately and halt the line".\n- Recent deviations for the line are found in `public.deviations` for `equipment_id` 4 and 5.\n- Cross-reference operator shifts using the `public.operators` table.\n- Run the **deviation_rate_by_line** metric against the last 24 hours.\n\n## When to reference\n- When the rolling 24-hour deviation rate for Line B exceeds the 1.0 threshold.\n- Following an operator report of unusual sounds from Filler-B1 or a high-severity quality check failure.	{"document_id": 1, "content_hash": "0b1adb3fa1e80410db74e1273708b4f5"}	aa5a32dadc3a1b16807d498665e3db7d	ready	2026-05-19 19:17:13.34671+00	2026-05-19 19:17:13.34671+00	2026-05-16 19:18:25.082809+00	2026-05-19 19:17:13.34671+00	13	source	documents	\N	\N
5	tables	public.operators	public.operators	Table · 8 rows	# public.operators\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\nThe `operators` table has 5 columns and 8 rows.\n\n\n<!-- provenance: claude, 2026-05-19, model=deepseek/deepseek-chat-v3.1 -->\n## What this table represents\nRecords each production line operator employed in the facility, including their assigned shift and the specific manufacturing lines they are qualified to operate. It tracks their hiring date and certifications.\n\n## Common joins\nNone obvious from this profile.\n\n## Column meanings\n- `operator_id` — Unique identifier for a production floor operator.\n- `full_name` — The legal name of the operator.\n- `shift` — The assigned work schedule (`day`, `swing`, or `night`).\n- `certified_lines` — An array of production line IDs (e.g., `LINE-A`) the operator is authorized to run.\n- `hired_at` — The date the operator was hired.\n\n## Likely filter patterns\n- `WHERE full_name ILIKE '%search_term%'` — Searching for operators by name (observed in most recent queries).\n- `WHERE shift = 'day'` (or `'swing'`, `'night'`) — Filtering operators by their assigned work shift.\n- `WHERE hired_at >= 'yyyy-mm-dd'` — Finding operators hired after a certain date.\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n## Columns\n\n| Column | Type | Null rate | Distinct | PK | FK |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n| `operator_id` | integer | 0.0% | 8 | ✓ |  |\n| `full_name` | text | 0.0% | 8 |  |  |\n| `shift` | text | 0.0% | 3 |  |  |\n| `certified_lines` | ARRAY | 0.0% | 7 |  |  |\n| `hired_at` | date | 0.0% | 8 |  |  |\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `operator_id` (integer)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 8\n- Min: `1`\n- Max: `8`\n- Top values:\n  - `2` (1)\n  - `6` (1)\n  - `8` (1)\n  - `4` (1)\n  - `3` (1)\n- Histogram (10 bins): 1:1, 10:1, 2:1, 3:1, 5:1, 6:1, 8:1, 9:1\n- Sample values: `1`, `2`, `3`, `4`, `5`\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `full_name` (text)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 8\n- Min: `Aiko Tanaka`\n- Max: `Tomasz Nowak`\n- Top values:\n  - `Maria Alvarez` (1)\n  - `Devon Park` (1)\n  - `Aiko Tanaka` (1)\n  - `Priya Shah` (1)\n  - `Tomasz Nowak` (1)\n- Sample values: `Aiko Tanaka`, `Brendan Kelly`, `Devon Park`, `Hassan Idris`, `Maria Alvarez`\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `shift` (text)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 3\n- Min: `day`\n- Max: `swing`\n- Top values:\n  - `day` (3)\n  - `swing` (3)\n  - `night` (2)\n- Sample values: `day`, `night`, `swing`\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `certified_lines` (ARRAY)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 7\n- Top values:\n  - `{LINE-C,LINE-D}` (2)\n  - `{LINE-A,LINE-B}` (1)\n  - `{LINE-A,LINE-D}` (1)\n  - `{LINE-B}` (1)\n  - `{LINE-A,LINE-B,LINE-D}` (1)\n- Sample values: `{LINE-A,LINE-B}`, `{LINE-A,LINE-B,LINE-D}`, `{LINE-A,LINE-C,LINE-D}`, `{LINE-A,LINE-D}`, `{LINE-B}`\n\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n### `hired_at` (date)\n\n- Null rate: 0.0%\n- Distinct values: 8\n- Min: `2019-06-21`\n- Max: `2025-04-11`\n- Top values:\n  - `2021-08-02` (1)\n  - `2025-04-11` (1)\n  - `2024-02-05` (1)\n  - `2022-09-08` (1)\n  - `2019-06-21` (1)\n- Sample values: `2019-06-21`, `2020-11-30`, `2021-08-02`, `2022-03-14`, `2022-09-08`\n\n\n\n## Used in views\n\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_operator_deviation_performance_60d]] — Operator performance metrics showing deviations per completed run (auto-seeded by Loom. Reason: Operations managers need to evaluate operator performance by comparing deviation rates across operators and shifts)\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_operators_d6cbb6]] — Auto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "who is naruto?"\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_operator_certified_line_summary]] — Shows operators with their shift, certifications, and counts of recent completed runs to assess workload and line specialization. (auto-seeded by Loom. Reason: Links operator certification and shift data to their actual production activity, useful for resource planning and skill matching.)\n- [[tables/loom_views.v_operator_performance_metrics_90d]] — Operator performance metrics including production volume and deviation rates by shift for the last 90 days (auto-seeded by Loom. Reason: Evaluates operator effectiveness across shifts, helping with workforce management and training allocation)\n	{"name": "operators", "schema": "public", "is_view": false, "table_id": 3}	25617ca6c7b73845b9035488ddcb720c	ready	2026-05-20 08:54:07.952606+00	2026-05-20 08:54:07.952606+00	2026-05-16 19:16:28.351284+00	2026-05-20 08:54:07.952606+00	18	source	tables	\N	\N
