60	docs	iche9	ich_e9.pdf	This ICH E9 guideline establishes statistical principles for the design, conduct, analysis, and evaluation of clinical trials of medicinal products, intended for statisticians, clinicians, and regulat	## What it is\nThis ICH E9 guideline establishes statistical principles for the design, conduct, analysis, and evaluation of clinical trials of medicinal products, intended for statisticians, clinicians, and regulatory professionals involved in drug development.\n\n## Key points\n*   Defines a **confirmatory trial** as "an adequately controlled trial in which the hypotheses are stated in advance and evaluated."\n*   Distinguishes confirmatory trials from **exploratory trials**, which may help form hypotheses for future studies.\n*   Emphasizes design techniques to avoid bias, specifically highlighting **blinding** and **randomisation**.\n*   The primary treatment effect is typically "a comparison (or contrast) of two or more treatments."\n*   Defines a **Trial Statistician** as the person responsible for the statistical aspects of the trial.\n*   Defines a **Treatment Emergent** event as one that emerges during treatment or worsens relative to the pre-treatment state.\n\n## When to reference\n*   When designing a clinical trial protocol and defining its statistical aspects.\n*   To establish the standard definitions for trial types (confirmatory vs. exploratory) and key variables (primary, secondary, surrogate).	{"document_id": 3, "content_hash": "3228eeb1a85764b93861067dcbd4cd8e"}	29244a099cc72f43b18162d96c03d37f	ready	2026-05-19 19:19:44.41277+00	2026-05-19 19:19:44.41277+00	2026-05-19 19:17:28.511464+00	2026-05-19 19:19:44.41277+00	13	source	documents	\N	\N
44	tables	loom_views.v_deviations_8c28a8	loom_views.v_deviations_8c28a8  (view)	Saved view · 24 rows	# loom_views.v_deviations_8c28a8\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\nThis is a **view** created by Loom. 24 rows as of 2026-05-18.\n\n<!-- provenance: claude, 2026-05-18 -->\n## What this view represents\nAuto-saved by Loom because the underlying query had aggregation/filters and was likely to be re-asked. Originated from: "Why line b?"\n\n## Definition\n\n```sql\nSELECT \n  pr.line_id,\n  d.category,\n  COUNT(*) as deviation_count,\n  COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE d.actual_value <> d.expected_value) as mismatch_count,\n  COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE d.actual_value <> d.expected_value)::float / NULLIF(COUNT(*), 0) as mismatch_rate\nFROM public.deviations d\nJOIN public.production_runs pr ON d.run_id = pr.run_id\nWHERE d.observed_at >= NOW() - INTERVAL '30 days'\nGROUP BY pr.line_id, d.category\nORDER BY pr.line_id, deviation_count DESC\n```\n\n<!-- provenance: schema -->\n## Columns\n\n| Column | Type |\n| --- | --- |\n| `line_id` | text |\n| `category` | text |\n| `deviation_count` | bigint |\n| `mismatch_count` | bigint |\n| `mismatch_rate` | double precision |\n\n	{"name": "v_deviations_8c28a8", "schema": "loom_views", "is_view": true, "table_id": 2123}	2a772139fd8b08ba69020bea2cff2622	ready	2026-05-18 06:18:27.189244+00	2026-05-20 08:54:07.883953+00	2026-05-18 06:18:27.189244+00	2026-05-18 06:18:27.189244+00	\N	source	tables	\N	\N
